### Description

I know that Signal Forms are experimental, but I'm wondering if I'm missing something in their intended use, or if I cannot find the documentation for my use-case.

I would like to create a Component that accepts a form model and schema as signal inputs, and displays a signal-based form. The use case would be a form to Add/Edit an entity, where validations are quite different, but model and presentation are (almost) the same.

As far as I understand, form() needs to be called in dependency injection context, so I cannot use a schema taken from an input signal, because it would not yet hold a value.

I know I could add "flags" on the model, and add conditions in the form schema, but I wanted to try a solution where the model is not filled with these kinds of flags, and schemas are really different depending on the context.

My ideal solution would be something similar to this:

```
@Component({ ... })
export class EntityFormComponent {
    // entity model, passed as component input
    entity = input.required<IEntityModel>();
    // entity form schema, passed as component input, could be different depending on the page that uses this component
    schema = input<Schema<IEntityModel>>();
    // form signal
    formSignal = linkedSignal(this.model);
	// form tree
    formTree: FieldTree<IUserModel>;

	constructor() {
		// here, formTree creation works, but schema signal does not yet have a value
		this.formTree = form(this.formSignal, this.schema());
	}

	ngAfterViewInit() {
		// here, schema signal has value, but formTree creation fails, because form() needs to be called in dependency injection context
		this.formTree = form(this.formSignal, this.schema());
	}
}

```

### Proposed solution

Add the possibility to update the form schema after the form is implemented, to be able to do something like:

```
@Component({ ... })
export class EntityFormComponent {
    // entity model, passed as component input
    entity = input.required<IEntityModel>();
    // entity form schema, passed as component input, could be different depending on the page that uses this component
    schema = input<Schema<IEntityModel>>();
    // form signal
    formSignal = linkedSignal(this.model);
	// form tree creation
    formTree: FieldTree<IUserModel> = form(this.formSignal, this.schema());

	ngAfterViewInit() {
		// set form schema when schema signal has value
		this.formTree.updateSchema(this.schema());
	}
}
```

If I'm missing something from the documentation of the experimental feature, I apologize in advance :) 

### Alternatives considered

An alternative would be to have the FormTree initialized after the constructor phase has completed, but I guess this would be against the general signal patterns.

